# LINUX NOTES CHEAT SHEET — BASIC STRUCTURE

## LOCATION / NAVIGATION

Go to your notes folder:

```
cd ~/Reid_Maxim
```

Check where you are:

```
pwd
```

See files in folder:

```
ls
```

## BASIC COMMAND STRUCTURE

Most commands follow this pattern:

```
command [options] input > output
```

Example:

```
grep -i "word" file.txt > output.txt
```

command = what you are doing
options = extra behavior (-i, -C, etc)
input = file(s) to read

> = redirect output into file
> output = file to save results

## GREP (SEARCH TEXT)

Search for a word:

```
grep "grep" maxim_01.txt
```

Ignore uppercase/lowercase:

```
grep -i "grep" maxim_01.txt
```

Keep context (lines before/after):

```
grep -i -C 3 "grep" maxim_01.txt
```

Search ALL 5 note files:

```
grep -i -C 3 "grep" maxim_0*.txt
```

Include filename in results:

```
grep -i -H -C 3 "grep" maxim_0*.txt
```

## REDIRECTION (SAVE OUTPUT)

Overwrite file:

```
> output.txt
```

Append to file:

```
>> output.txt
```

Example:

```
grep -i "grep" maxim_0*.txt > touched.txt
```

## IMPORTANT RULE

Never use the output file as input.

BAD (causes error):

```
grep "grep" *.txt > touched.txt
```

if touched.txt matches *.txt

## PIPING ( | )

Pipe sends output from one command into another:

```
command1 | command2
```

Example — extract URL and open browser:

```
grep -Eo 'https?://[^ ]+' maxim_0*.txt | head -n 1 | xargs qutebrowser
```

## COMMON PIPE PARTS

head -n 1     = take first result
sort -u       = remove duplicates
xargs         = pass result as command input

## FILE CREATION

Create empty file:

```
touch touched.txt
```

Create file from command output:

```
grep "grep" maxim_0*.txt > touched.txt
```

## USER MANAGEMENT (BASIC)

Create user:

```
sudo useradd -m username
```

Set password:

```
sudo passwd username
```

## LIST ALL USERS

All users are stored here:

```
/etc/passwd
```

Save usernames only:

```
cut -d: -f1 /etc/passwd > winners.txt
```

## QUICK WORKFLOW (YOUR LAB FLOW)

